If you want to generate QR codes without relying on external libraries or downloads, you can use a QR code API service to generate the QR codes dynamically. Here's an updated version of the JavaScript file that uses the `fetch` API to request a QR code image from an API and display it:

JavaScript file (script.js):
```javascript
// script.js

document.getElementById("generateBtn").addEventListener("click", function() {
  var qrText = this.textContent; // Button's text will be used as the text for the QR code

  fetch(`https://api.qrserver.com/v1/create-qr-code/?size=150x150&data=${qrText}`)
    .then(response => response.blob())
    .then(blob => {
      var qrCodeDiv = document.createElement("div");
      qrCodeDiv.style.width = "300px";
      qrCodeDiv.style.height = "150px";

      var qrImage = document.createElement("img");
      qrImage.src = URL.createObjectURL(blob);

      qrCodeDiv.appendChild(qrImage);
      document.getElementById("qrCodesContainer").appendChild(qrCodeDiv);
    })
    .catch(error => console.error('Error generating QR code:', error));
});
```

In this version, the JavaScript code makes a request to the `api.qrserver.com` API to generate a QR code image based on the button's text. The generated QR code image is then displayed in a dynamically created `div` element. This approach allows you to generate QR codes without any additional downloads or libraries.

